title: Fix: Auto-reconnect not triggered on ping timeout - NodeTimeoutException not caught
stack_trace: When ping requests fail with `NodeTimeoutException`, the exception is not caught properly in `IqStreamNodeHandler.sendPing()`. The method only catches `SessionClosedException`, which means:

Exception in thread "ForkJoinPool.commonPool-worker-3" com.github.auties00.cobalt.exception.NodeTimeoutException: Node[description=iq, attributes={to=s.whatsapp.net, xmlns=w:p, type=get, id=C47E6EC8FF}, children=[Node[description=ping]]]
The catch block only handles `SessionClosedException`, but `whatsapp.sendNode()` can also throw `NodeTimeoutException` when the 60-second timeout expires in `SocketRequest.waitForResponse()`.
Add `NodeTimeoutException` to the catch block to properly handle ping timeouts:

Wrap new `Rating(rating)` in a try/catch and rethrow as `IllegalValueException` with `Rating.MESSAGE_CONSTRAINTS`, or

title: [BUG] OkHttpFluxRequestBody does not correctly propagate IOExceptions
stack_trace: We are seeing unhandled exception logs when a `java.net.SocketException` occurs during connection creation.

I believe the issues is that [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/19b07befe4080f7a0a3a03dc13bb12f43bd7240e/sdk/core/azure-core-http-okhttp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/http/okhttp/implementation/OkHttpFluxRequestBody.java#L92-L94) in the implementation of the okhttp `RequestBody` it is expected to throw an `IOException`.

There are various points in the stack trace where okhttp can gracefully handle `IOExceptions`, see for example the [RetryAndFollowUpInterceptor](https://github.com/square/okhttp/blob/c3f052fd9454bcc1f395346a92109e7be4282760/okhttp/src/commonJvmAndroid/kotlin/okhttp3/internal/http/RetryAndFollowUpInterceptor.kt#L76).
However, the custom `OkHttpFluxRequestBody` is propagating the SocketException wrapped in a `reactor.core.Exceptions$ReactiveException` so this is not handled correctly.
I would like to contribute a PR where the affected code path is wrapped in a try catch block and in case the ReactiveException is caused by an IOException then the IOException is thrown.
Exception in thread "OkHttp Dispatcher" reactor.core.Exceptions$ReactiveException: java.net.SocketException: Connection reset by peer
Caused by: java.net.SocketException: Connection reset by peer
The original IOException is propagated correctly

stack_trace: If a `ReplyMessage` arrives with a `ref` that is not in `messages_waiting_for_ack`, this raises a `KeyError`. Since `_listen` in `client.py` only catches `ConnectionClosedError`, the unhandled `KeyError` kills the `_listen` task entirely, making the connection unrecoverable.
The `KeyError` crashed the `_listen` task, which prevented the rejoin response from being processed. The channel got permanently stuck in `joining` state.
Run the snippet above and wait for a WebSocket disconnection (close code 1006). The `_listen` task will crash with a `KeyError` when processing a reply with a stale ref during reconnection.

title: PanicException when observer callback raises an exception
stack_trace: When an observer callback raises an exception, pycrdt panics with `SystemError('<built-in function time_ns> returned a result with an exception set')` instead of propagating the original exception. Here is a repro:

Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
    raise ValueError("Observer exploded!!")
") }

pyo3_runtime.PanicException: Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
    raise ValueError("Observer exploded!")
") }

After the observer runs, yrs calls `Clock::now()` to get a timestamp. The timestamp function calls `time_ns()`, which is a C builtin. When a C function returns successfully while an exception is set in Python's interpreter state, Python raises `SystemError("returned a result with an exception set")`. The `.expect()` then panics.
knowledge_text:
Error Type: SystemError
When an observer callback raises an exception, pycrdt panics with `SystemError('<built-in function time_ns> returned a result with an exception set')` instead of propagating the original exception. Here is a repro:
raise ValueError("Observer exploded!")
File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 10, in main
File "pycrdt/_transaction.py", line 78, in __exit__
pyo3_runtime.PanicException: Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py\", line 4, in bad_timestamp\n    raise ValueError(\"Observer exploded!\")\n") }
After the observer runs, yrs calls `Clock::now()` to get a timestamp. The timestamp function calls `time_ns()`, which is a C builtin. When a C function returns successfully while an exception is set in Python's interpreter state, Python raises `SystemError("returned a result with an exception set")`. The `.expect()` then panics.
Root Cause: Root cause not explicitly documented.

title: Silent 'failure' of `__setitem__` with out-of-range indices
stack_trace: An `IndexError` is raised if a user attempts to index with an inappropriate index or indices a Field's data (as supported as a method via the Field directly in cf-python but not in cfdm, it seems) in the context of `__getitem__`, but for `__setitem__` there is no indication that anything is wrong:
IndexError: Index [(slice(0, 1, 1), slice(100, 101, 1))] selects no elements from data with shape (5, 8)

So the question is: **should we raise also an `IndexError` for `__setitem__` as for `__getitem__` with invalid indices**? I would argue we _should_, as it gives consistent behaviour across those two related methods, and it prevents the chance of confusion as to why item setting didn't seem to work when the user doesn't realise the indexes are not valid (like myself, see below!). And as for the argument of 'what does NumPy / the Python Array API Standard do / say we should do, indeed they raise the `IndexError` in both cases:
